This script builds a robust trend line using RANSAC + linear regression instead of fitting all points blindly, so it can ignore outlier bars and focus on the dominant price trend. In Pine terms, it stores the last length bars in arrays, repeatedly tests random 2-point line candidates, keeps the candidate with the most inliers, then draws the fitted line, threshold margin, and RMSE-based channel.

Big picture
Ordinary linear regression uses all points, so a few extreme candles can pull the trend line badly off course. RANSAC works differently: it randomly samples a minimal subset, fits a candidate model, measures residuals for all points, labels points within a threshold as inliers, and keeps the model with the strongest consensus set.

In this script, the “minimal subset” is just 2 points because a straight line is fully defined by two points. After a candidate line is formed, every stored bar is checked against it, and bars whose absolute price error is below threshold become “true inliers.”

Inputs
length, widthMult, and src control the lookback window, channel width multiplier, and source series used to build the regression. The script stores only the latest length points, so all modeling happens on a rolling window rather than the full chart history.

The RANSAC inputs control the robustness test: inlineN is the minimum acceptable inlier count, errorType chooses automatic or fixed residual tolerance, minError is the tolerance value or multiplier, and maxIter is how many random models to try. In RANSAC generally, the inlier threshold and number of rounds are the key hyperparameters because they determine how tolerant the fit is and how likely the algorithm is to find a good consensus set.

Custom type
The type LinearRegression block defines a user-defined type that stores the x-values, y-values, inlier x-values, inlier y-values, and the fitted coefficients a and b. This is Pine’s way of bundling data together so methods can operate on one object instead of many loose variables.

The model represents the line 
y
