a
x
+
b
y=ax+b, where a is slope and b is intercept. The separate inliners_* arrays are used later so the script can mark which bars were accepted by the final RANSAC fit.

Methods
fit() computes the slope with covariance(y, x) / variance(x) and the intercept with avg(y) - a * avg(x), which is the standard closed-form least-squares solution for a straight line. Pine arrays support statistics like avg, covariance, and variance, so the script can fit regression directly from the stored arrays.

predict(x) returns the y-value on the fitted line for a given x-position. rmse() loops through all points in the current model, sums squared prediction errors, divides by the number of points, and takes the square root, which gives the root-mean-square error used later to size the channel.

Data collection
The script uses var y and var x so the arrays persist across bars. Each bar, it pushes the newest source value and bar_index to the front with unshift(), then removes the oldest item with pop() once the arrays exceed length.

That means y[0] and x[0] are the newest stored point, while older bars move deeper into the arrays. Conceptually, this creates a rolling regression dataset of the last length bars.

Threshold logic
When errorType is Fixed, the inlier threshold is simply minError. When it is Auto, the threshold is based on cumulative average candle body size, computed as ta.cum(abs(close - open)) / (n + 1) * minError, so the tolerance scales with typical market movement.

That auto mode is a heuristic, not a textbook RANSAC threshold. Standard RANSAC usually uses a residual threshold tied to expected noise scale, but this script approximates that scale from average candle movement.

Core RANSAC loop
The heavy work runs only inside if barstate.islastconfirmedhistory, which means Pine waits until the last historical bar to do this expensive search. TradingView documents this flag as true on the dataset’s last historical bar, making it useful for postponing server-intensive calculations.

Inside the loop, the script:

Picks 2 random indices from the stored window.

Builds a temporary line from those 2 points.

Tests every stored bar against that line.

Keeps bars whose absolute residual is below threshold.

If that inlier set is larger than the best one seen so far, it refits using all those inliers and saves it as final_model.

This is classic RANSAC structure: sample, fit, score by inlier count, then refit on the consensus set. One limitation is that ties are broken only by larger inlier count; unlike many RANSAC implementations, it does not compare residual quality when two models have the same inlier count.

Drawing logic
After the best model is found, the script predicts two endpoints: one at n - length + 1 and one at n. It then draws the regression line across the window and extends it to the right.

If showMargin is enabled, it draws a band at ±threshold around the line, which visually shows the inlier acceptance zone. If showChannel is enabled, it computes RMSE on the full window and draws a wider channel at ±(rmse * widthMult), which behaves more like a volatility envelope around the fitted trend.

Inliers and outliers
Before calculating channel width, the script temporarily replaces final_model.y and final_model.x with the full rolling dataset so rmse() is measured on all recent bars, not only inliers. That means the displayed channel reflects total fit error across the whole lookback window.

Finally, it loops through each stored bar and checks whether that bar’s x-coordinate exists in final_model.inliners_x. If yes, it plots a blue dot label for an inlier; otherwise, it plots a red dot label for an outlier.

Important issues
There is a likely typo throughout the code: inliners should be inliers. The script is consistent internally, so it still works, but renaming it would improve readability.

There is also a subtle issue in the random sampling step: the two random indices can be the same, which can produce duplicate points and a bad candidate fit. Because regression slope divides by variance(x), duplicate x-values risk zero variance and an invalid fit.

Another practical issue is that the script creates new lines and labels on each last-history execution without deleting old ones. In some indicator designs, that can clutter resources over time unless managed with persistent IDs and line.delete() or label.delete(). TradingView’s bar-state docs explain why last-bar execution is often used to control expensive drawing logic, but object lifecycle still needs care.

Plain English version
You can think of it like this:

Gather the last 100 bars.

Randomly draw a line through 2 of them.

Ask: “How many of the other bars sit close enough to this line?”

Repeat thousands of times.

Keep the line that has the biggest crowd agreeing with it.

Refit the line using only that agreeing crowd.

Mark the agreeing bars as inliers and the rest as outliers.

Good modifications
Here are the most useful ways to modify it:

Safer sampling: Force the two random indices to be different, which avoids degenerate candidate lines.

Better model selection: If two models have the same inlier count, choose the one with lower residual error, which is how many RANSAC variants improve stability.

Use source consistently: The auto threshold uses close and open, even if src is not close; you may want thresholding based on the chosen source or ATR instead.

Realtime updates: Replace barstate.islastconfirmedhistory with logic that also updates on the live bar if you want the trend line to move in realtime, though that will cost more computation.

Use standard deviation or ATR channel: Instead of RMSE on all points, derive channel width from inliers only, ATR, or standard deviation for a different visual behavior.

